<br>
What constitutes a personal attack I think depends a lot on the motivation of the writer, and can also depend on the attitude of the reader.  Generally, I consider a personal attack to be something that has no other purpose than to hurt someone.  Telling someone that they were out of line in some instance, or that you don't think they should have done something, or that you just generally don't like them usually isn't really an attack - there are ways you can go about it that might make it into that, sure, but in those cases you're usually targeting something they did/said rather than what they are.<br>
<br>
Some people are sensitive, though, and might go off the handle from someone saying &quot;You are wrong.&quot;  My opinion is that it's their fault.  <br>
<br>
As for why the reader configures into this - if the attack doesn't faze them, and they just continue posting as normal and not throwing hysterics, reporting the offender, getting defensive, or flaming back, then the personal attack will most likely just slide (in most situations; depends also on the attentiveness of the moderators and other readers).<br>
<br>
Generally, before you post something you think is questionable, consider what your own response would be if someone said it to you; if your reaction would be to get upset and go on the defensive, then it's probably a personal attack.<br>
<br>
